{"cursor":"13384","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox writer  |name = |caption = Jean AmÃ©ry\n|image = |caption = |image_alt = |birth_name = Hanns Chaim Mayer |birth_date =\n|birth_place = Vienna, Austria-Hungary |nationality = Austrian |death_date =\n|death_place = Salzburg, Austria |occupation = Author |genre = |movement =\n|spouse = |children = |religion = Roman Catholic |influences = |influenced =\n|awards = |signature = }}\n\n'Jean AmÃ©ry' (October 31, 1912 â October 17, 1978), born 'Hanns Chaim Mayer',\nwas an Austrian essayist whose work was often informed by his experiences during\nWorld War II. Formerly a philosophy and literature student in Vienna, AmÃ©ry's\nparticipation in organized resistance against the Nazi occupation of Belgium\nresulted in his detainment and torture by the Gestapo, and several years of\nimprisonment in concentration camps.\n\nAmÃ©ry survived internments in Auschwitz and Buchenwald, and was finally\nliberated at Bergen-Belsen in 1945. His most celebrated work, At the Mind's\nLimits: Contemplations by a Survivor on Auschwitz and Its Realities, suggests\nthat torture was \"the essence\" of the Third Reich. Other notable works included\nOn Aging and On Suicide: A Discourse on Voluntary Death.\n\nAmÃ©ry committed suicide by taking an overdose of sleeping pills in 1978.\n","linknr":207,"url":"Jean_Améry","recorded":1375059100,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Jean_Am%C3%A9ry&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Jean_Am%C3%A9ry&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin